Bobby Briggs.

5
00:02:20,487 --> 00:02:23,217
Bobby, you know
what you have to have in this life?

6
00:02:25,926 --> 00:02:27,757
Balance.

7
00:02:28,728 --> 00:02:30,753
Distance.

8
00:02:31,731 --> 00:02:33,699
Symmetry.

9
00:02:40,006 --> 00:02:41,564
Look.

10
00:02:43,577 --> 00:02:45,807
lt's a beautiful thing, isn't it?

11
00:02:50,917 --> 00:02:54,011
Mr. Horne, did you listen
to that tape that l sent you?

12
00:02:54,221 --> 00:02:56,018
Yes, l listened to your tape, Bobby.

13
00:02:56,256 --> 00:03:00,818
Frankly, l am surprised
that Leo could master the technology.

14
00:03:04,764 --> 00:03:06,425
Damn it, Bobby, what do you want?

15
00:03:08,001 --> 00:03:11,459
Mr. Horne,
l have a great admiration for you.

16
00:03:11,671 --> 00:03:14,834
Admiration is for poets
and dairy cows, Bobby.

17
00:03:15,008 --> 00:03:19,274
l don't know what you mean. l...

18
00:03:20,013 --> 00:03:21,674
Bobby.

19
00:03:24,818 --> 00:03:29,312
You're standing in front
of a mammoth skyscraper.

20
00:03:29,523 --> 00:03:33,118
A leviathan that rips a hole
in the clouds.

21
00:03:33,293 --> 00:03:37,127
Now, what's the first question
that comes to your mind?

22
00:03:45,138 --> 00:03:49,234
The first question that you ask yourself
is, ''What's on the top floor?''

23
00:03:49,409 --> 00:03:53,175
''Who's up there in the penthouse,
and why?''

24
00:03:53,647 --> 00:03:55,774
Now, that's who l am.

25
00:03:57,651 --> 00:03:59,278
Are you?

26
00:04:01,821 --> 00:04:05,348
Yeah, of course l am. Yes.

27
00:04:09,195 --> 00:04:13,859
Bobby, opportunity knocks.

28
00:04:17,003 --> 00:04:22,669
l want you to follow Hank Jennings.

29
00:04:23,009 --> 00:04:26,376
l want you to chronicle
his existence.

30
00:04:26,546 --> 00:04:30,949
Show me something
that l don't already know.

31
00:04:47,233 --> 00:04:48,962
l'd like to see both.

32
00:04:49,135 --> 00:04:52,400
Very good. Which one
would you like to see first?

33
00:04:53,707 --> 00:04:55,197
Well...

34
00:05:12,659 --> 00:05:14,092
What is this?

35
00:05:15,061 --> 00:05:16,926
l'd thought l'd taken that out.

36
00:05:17,097 --> 00:05:20,396
That property
is called Dead Dog Farm.

37
00:05:20,567 --> 00:05:23,092
And it's worse than it sounds.

38
00:05:23,269 --> 00:05:25,464
- What is it?
- A puzzle.

39
00:05:25,672 --> 00:05:28,140
No one ever really stays there long.

40
00:05:28,308 --> 00:05:30,071
When can l see it?

41
00:05:34,280 --> 00:05:35,508
Sorry l'm late.

42
00:05:35,682 --> 00:05:38,150
But the little nipper is so excited
about our camping trip,

43
00:05:38,318 --> 00:05:40,752
l just couldn't coax him
out of the car.

44
00:05:40,920 --> 00:05:42,581
Richard, this is Judy Swain

45
00:05:42,756 --> 00:05:45,418
from the Happy Helping Hands
organization.

46
00:05:45,592 --> 00:05:47,082
l'm little Nicky's case manager.

47
00:05:47,260 --> 00:05:49,854
Charmed, l'm sure. Shall we?

48
00:05:50,030 --> 00:05:52,089
Sit down.

49
00:05:52,265 --> 00:05:54,130
Okay.

50
00:05:55,602 --> 00:05:58,935
As l was about to tell your friends,

51
00:05:59,105 --> 00:06:02,131
the number one thing
to know about Nicky

52
00:06:02,308 --> 00:06:07,803
is that throughout his brief life,
he has been very confused,

53
00:06:07,981 --> 00:06:13,544
and perhaps traumatized
by a persistent random misfortune.

54
00:06:14,421 --> 00:06:17,151
Looks like he's bounced around
quite a bit.

55
00:06:17,323 --> 00:06:18,620
Well, yes, he has.

56
00:06:18,825 --> 00:06:20,884
- Poor child.
- Yes.

57
00:06:21,061 --> 00:06:22,460
An orphan, you know.

58
00:06:22,629 --> 00:06:25,029
Really? What happened?
Did his parents die?

59
00:06:25,932 --> 00:06:28,560
Nicely deduced, Andrew.

60
00:06:28,735 --> 00:06:31,033
Persistent random misfortune?

61
00:06:31,805 --> 00:06:33,238
They were killed.

62
00:06:33,740 --> 00:06:36,174
How were they killed, Miss Swain?

63
00:06:36,543 --> 00:06:38,238
Mysterious circumstances.

64
00:06:38,445 --> 00:06:42,575
l'm afraid the orphanage has never
provided us with that information.

65
00:06:43,483 --> 00:06:47,214
Andy, let's go.
Emergency up at the Great Northern.

66
00:07:03,703 --> 00:07:05,864
Looks like a heart attack.

67
00:07:06,339 --> 00:07:10,366
Once stimulated,
the female will respond in such a way

68
00:07:10,543 --> 00:07:14,172
that the skin around her...
Oh, my God.

69
00:07:14,347 --> 00:07:17,043
Looks like Dougie went out
with his boots on.

70
00:07:17,584 --> 00:07:22,078
Love Poems of Lord Byron,
The Kama Sutra,

71
00:07:22,689 --> 00:07:24,350
Hookers and Handmaidens.

72
00:07:25,058 --> 00:07:27,424
Sheriff, look at this.

73
00:07:32,532 --> 00:07:35,399
What a falling out was here.

74
00:07:43,576 --> 00:07:45,305
Doug.

75
00:07:46,780 --> 00:07:51,513
Lord, l hate to say it, l told you so.

76
00:08:01,795 --> 00:08:02,887
Here, sheriff.

77
00:08:04,898 --> 00:08:06,388
This is it.

78
00:08:06,599 --> 00:08:08,658
The murder weapon.

79
00:08:09,469 --> 00:08:13,428
She might as well
have blown his brains out with a rifle.

80
00:08:21,281 --> 00:08:25,115
He never could say no to a woman.

81
00:08:32,325 --> 00:08:34,657
You old fool.

82
00:08:49,976 --> 00:08:54,174
You sexual adventuress,
you'll burn in hell for this.

83
00:08:54,347 --> 00:08:58,716
- Take it easy, mister.
- l'm gonna shout till l wake the dead.

84
00:08:58,885 --> 00:09:01,217
She murdered my brother.

85
00:09:01,387 --> 00:09:04,151
She's a witch.

86
00:09:04,891 --> 00:09:08,292
He's right, l'm cursed.

87
00:09:08,461 --> 00:09:09,792
Don't be silly.

88
00:09:09,963 --> 00:09:13,592
No, no, it's true.

89
00:09:14,133 --> 00:09:18,968
lt all started in high school,
prom night.

90
00:09:19,405 --> 00:09:22,067
My date went to kiss me.

91
00:09:22,242 --> 00:09:25,837
lt was his first day
with his new braces.

92
00:09:26,012 --> 00:09:29,379
Oh, and they gleamed
in the moonlight.

93
00:09:30,683 --> 00:09:35,086
And his rubber band snapped
and his jaw locked open,

94
00:09:35,255 --> 00:09:37,723
and we ended up
in the emergency room,

95
00:09:37,891 --> 00:09:41,383
and the doctors had to break his jaw
in three places to get it to shut.

96
00:09:41,561 --> 00:09:46,362
And it's just gotten worse ever since.

97
00:09:46,566 --> 00:09:48,363
A curse needs a cure.

98
00:09:48,534 --> 00:09:51,094
l know a bit about these things.

99
00:09:51,271 --> 00:09:53,637
Are you the sheriff?

100
00:09:54,874 --> 00:10:00,835
Let's just say, when something
really big goes down, l'm the man.

101
00:10:06,719 --> 00:10:11,349
Boys, there's a story
about a great football coach,

102
00:10:11,524 --> 00:10:13,924
whose name escapes me
at this time,

103
00:10:14,093 --> 00:10:18,427
who was dead set against
having any black players on his team.

104
00:10:18,598 --> 00:10:24,036
Until somebody brought him the finest
black halfback anyone had ever seen.

105
00:10:24,203 --> 00:10:26,899
And when what's-his-name
saw him run 50 yards

106
00:10:27,073 --> 00:10:28,700
and no one lay a hand on him,

107
00:10:28,875 --> 00:10:32,436
he shouted, ''Look at that lndian go!''

108
00:10:32,612 --> 00:10:37,447
That coach accepted
that athlete's desire to compete.

109
00:10:37,951 --> 00:10:39,578
Nadine.

110
00:10:40,620 --> 00:10:44,317
And today, this story applies
to this woman's--

111
00:10:44,490 --> 00:10:47,550
This young girl's right to compete.

112
00:10:47,727 --> 00:10:52,289
ln addition to it being her moral
and constitutional right.

113
00:10:53,333 --> 00:10:56,996
Mike Nelson,
could you step up here for a second?

114
00:10:57,637 --> 00:10:59,127
Yeah.

115
00:10:59,973 --> 00:11:01,941
Come on, Mike, go.

116
00:11:02,342 --> 00:11:05,402
Now, Nadine has chosen
to prove herself to us

117
00:11:05,578 --> 00:11:08,479
by taking on our very best.

118
00:11:08,648 --> 00:11:12,084
Our very own district champion,
Mike Nelson.

119
00:11:12,251 --> 00:11:15,243
- Yeah! Come on. Come on.
- All right, man.

120
00:11:16,089 --> 00:11:17,488
Go, Mike.

121
00:11:17,657 --> 00:11:19,454
Hi, Mike.

122
00:11:21,094 --> 00:11:22,959
Put your hand here.

123
00:11:23,129 --> 00:11:24,653
No, here.

124
00:11:24,831 --> 00:11:27,527
All right, now just push against me.
l'll try not to hurt you.

125
00:11:27,734 --> 00:11:28,996
Wanna go out tonight?

126
00:11:29,168 --> 00:11:31,227
This is called a tie.

127
00:11:36,976 --> 00:11:38,341
- Oh, yeah.
- You stupid...

128
00:11:38,544 --> 00:11:39,875
What did you say, Mike?

129
00:11:46,686 --> 00:11:47,948
Neck, you're breaking my neck.

130
00:11:48,121 --> 00:11:50,487
You're right,
this is sort of like necking.

131
00:11:53,126 --> 00:11:56,391
What about tonight?

132
00:11:58,064 --> 00:11:59,656
Coach?

133
00:12:02,335 --> 00:12:03,962
Hey, coach?

134
00:12:08,674 --> 00:12:11,871
- Get up, Mike.
- Oh, my God.

135
00:12:12,545 --> 00:12:15,343
One, two and three.

136
00:12:15,515 --> 00:12:17,983
Now will you go out with me?

137
00:12:34,500 --> 00:12:36,400
What happened to you?

138
00:12:37,236 --> 00:12:38,863
l got beat up by a girl.

139
00:12:40,873 --> 00:12:42,272
What did you do to her?

140
00:12:42,442 --> 00:12:45,070
Donna, l'm not kidding.
Now, you've gotta help me.

141
00:12:45,244 --> 00:12:47,735
lt's bad enough getting stomped on
in front of the whole team,

142
00:12:47,914 --> 00:12:49,176
but she likes me.

143
00:12:49,348 --> 00:12:51,077
- Who?
- Mrs. Hurley.

144
00:12:52,085 --> 00:12:53,950
Nadine?

145
00:12:54,921 --> 00:12:55,945
lt's not funny.

146
00:12:56,122 --> 00:12:58,613
l don't know, maybe an older woman
is just what you need.

147
00:12:58,825 --> 00:13:01,623
l don't wanna go out with anyone
who can body-slam me.

148
00:13:01,828 --> 00:13:03,693
Well, what do you want me
to do about it?

149
00:13:03,863 --> 00:13:07,458
l don't know, talk to her or something.
Pretend you're still my girlfriend.

150
00:13:07,633 --> 00:13:09,464
Sorry, Mike,
l'm not that good of an actress.

151
00:13:09,635 --> 00:13:13,366
Donna, this is serious.
l'm gonna end up in traction.

152
00:13:25,918 --> 00:13:27,215
May l help you?

153
00:13:27,420 --> 00:13:29,547
Hang up a local service rebellion,

154
00:13:29,722 --> 00:13:33,624
wonder if you'd help me bundle up
loose sticks and burn that master.

155
00:13:33,793 --> 00:13:38,389
Malcolm, Malcolm Sloan,
as in brother to Evelyn.

156
00:13:38,564 --> 00:13:41,897
Mr. Marsh's driver, as in,
''Bring that car around, James.''

157
00:13:42,101 --> 00:13:44,160
So how badly
did she damage the Jag?

158
00:13:44,370 --> 00:13:45,632
lt's repairable.

159
00:13:46,372 --> 00:13:50,103
That's the nice thing about things.

160
00:13:52,445 --> 00:13:54,504
You know, when she and Jeffrey
fell in love,

161
00:13:54,680 --> 00:13:56,443
he gave her a whole new life.

162
00:13:56,616 --> 00:13:58,516
That's for sure.

163
00:14:00,019 --> 00:14:04,922
Now l got a nice uniform,
and the keys to the liquor cabinet.

164
00:14:07,827 --> 00:14:09,454
God, l hope
l don't sound ungrateful,

165
00:14:09,629 --> 00:14:11,927
because compared
to the life l was living,

166
00:14:12,098 --> 00:14:15,033
wanton dissipation is a step up.

167
00:14:15,201 --> 00:14:16,998
And Evelyn,
she learned a lot herself.

168
00:14:17,470 --> 00:14:20,769
Defensive postures,
masking bruises, vicious cycles.

169
00:14:20,973 --> 00:14:22,668
What are you talking about?

170
00:14:23,342 --> 00:14:26,038
l'm sorry, am l being obscure?

171
00:14:26,512 --> 00:14:29,208
Once a fortnight,
Jeffrey pounds her mercilessly,

172
00:14:29,415 --> 00:14:33,146
and she tries to get even
by breaking one of his things.

173
00:14:34,120 --> 00:14:36,020
lt only perpetuates the cycle.

174
00:14:36,189 --> 00:14:38,521
She's your sister.
Why don't you stop him?

175
00:14:41,027 --> 00:14:44,360
Sonny boy,
nobody stops Mr. Marsh.

176
00:14:44,530 --> 00:14:47,727
That's a golden rule around here.

177
00:14:47,934 --> 00:14:50,300
You can jot that down
and put it under your pillow.

178
00:14:52,638 --> 00:14:54,731
l gotta get back.

179
00:14:56,242 --> 00:14:59,075
Hey, thanks.

180
00:14:59,845 --> 00:15:01,574
l mean that.

181
00:15:32,845 --> 00:15:35,905
Well, it's still standing.

182
00:15:36,082 --> 00:15:38,073
Almost by force of habit.

183
00:15:38,251 --> 00:15:41,709
Well, habit can provide
a strong foundation.

184
00:15:41,887 --> 00:15:43,684
Dead Dog Farm, huh?

185
00:15:43,856 --> 00:15:46,950
That's an old legend.
Of all the people in the world,

186
00:15:47,126 --> 00:15:50,186
the best and the worst
are drawn to Dead Dog,

187
00:15:50,363 --> 00:15:52,228
and most turn away.

188
00:15:52,398 --> 00:15:55,424
Only those with the purest of heart
can feel its pain.

189
00:15:55,601 --> 00:16:00,698
And somewhere in between,
the rest of us struggle.

190
00:16:01,140 --> 00:16:04,041
lrene, have you shown this property
to anyone else recently?

191
00:16:04,210 --> 00:16:07,771
l don't think anyone's asked
to see it this last year.

192
00:16:07,947 --> 00:16:09,938
There's three vehicles.

193
00:16:10,116 --> 00:16:14,018
A jeep, a four-wheeler
and a luxury sedan.

194
00:16:19,458 --> 00:16:21,517
lt's open.

195
00:16:22,528 --> 00:16:24,257
Hello?

196
00:16:28,768 --> 00:16:34,934
There's been a meeting here.
ln the past few hours.

197
00:16:46,352 --> 00:16:48,616
What are you seeing?

198
00:16:52,058 --> 00:16:55,084
They forgot
there was no running water.

199
00:17:03,936 --> 00:17:06,063
Baby laxative.

200
00:17:35,901 --> 00:17:38,392
More white powder.

201
00:17:44,810 --> 00:17:46,744
Cocaine.

202
00:17:47,179 --> 00:17:51,138
lrene, we have to notify the sheriff.

203
00:18:04,864 --> 00:18:07,230
Nicky, stop that, please.

204
00:18:15,174 --> 00:18:17,438
Nicky, stop it.

205
00:18:18,911 --> 00:18:21,345
l don't understand this at all.

206
00:18:22,281 --> 00:18:25,011
l just had the car checked
at Gas Farm.

207
00:18:26,685 --> 00:18:28,585
He told me it was
in perfect working order.

208
00:18:28,788 --> 00:18:31,450
Perfect working order.

209
00:18:33,392 --> 00:18:37,419
This is all so technical.

210
00:18:41,434 --> 00:18:45,461
Please, Nicky,
Uncle Dick is trying to read.

211
00:18:55,414 --> 00:18:57,780
Nicholas, get out of the car!

212
00:18:59,218 --> 00:19:01,277
Nicholas, out of the car, right now!

213
00:19:01,454 --> 00:19:03,979
Out of the car!

214
00:19:04,723 --> 00:19:06,486
Do you hear me?

215
00:19:09,695 --> 00:19:11,720
Are you mad at me, Uncle Dick?

216
00:19:11,897 --> 00:19:15,333
Well, of course l'm not mad at you.
Why should l be mad at you?

217
00:19:15,501 --> 00:19:17,731
Scared you, didn't l?

218
00:19:44,263 --> 00:19:45,958
Uncle Dick!

219
00:19:47,366 --> 00:19:49,800
Don't worry, don't worry,
l'm all right, little Nicky.

220
00:19:49,969 --> 00:19:53,530
What if you died?
You aren't gonna die, are you?

221
00:19:53,739 --> 00:19:57,334
Of course not. Don't be silly.

222
00:20:03,449 --> 00:20:04,473
Harry?

223
00:20:05,050 --> 00:20:07,041
Cooper. This is Colonel Riley.

224
00:20:07,253 --> 00:20:09,050
He's heading up
the Air Force's investigation

225
00:20:09,255 --> 00:20:10,654
into Briggs' disappearance.

226
00:20:10,823 --> 00:20:13,053
- Colonel.
- Cooper.

227
00:20:13,259 --> 00:20:15,989
You were with Briggs
when we lost our coordinates on him.

228
00:20:16,161 --> 00:20:17,526
Yes, l was.

229
00:20:17,763 --> 00:20:21,392
When you were at the site,
did you notice any wildlife in the area?

230
00:20:21,567 --> 00:20:24,798
- Wildlife?
- Birds, owls?

231
00:20:24,970 --> 00:20:26,631
Yes.

232
00:20:26,805 --> 00:20:30,969
Yes, just moments before the major
disappeared, l heard an owl.

233
00:20:31,577 --> 00:20:33,306
Any visual contact?

234
00:20:33,479 --> 00:20:36,880
Look, colonel, Garland Briggs
is a good friend of mine.

235
00:20:37,049 --> 00:20:39,415
lt would be a lot better
if you'd just level with us.

236
00:20:39,652 --> 00:20:42,712
We know about the monitors
and the messages from deep space

237
00:20:42,888 --> 00:20:44,856
that you received pertaining to me.

238
00:20:45,291 --> 00:20:49,853
You may know something,
but you best get your facts straight.

239
00:20:50,029 --> 00:20:52,827
Our monitors are pointed
at deep space,

240
00:20:52,998 --> 00:20:57,697
but the messages we intercepted
that Briggs showed you

241
00:20:57,870 --> 00:21:01,397
were sent from right here
in these woods.

242
00:21:01,607 --> 00:21:05,737
Now, where they were sent to
is another question.

243
00:21:06,512 --> 00:21:10,414
Might this have something to do
with a place called the White Lodge?

244
00:21:11,417 --> 00:21:13,214
That's classified.

245
00:21:13,385 --> 00:21:15,182
Colonel, we'd like to help you,

246
00:21:15,354 --> 00:21:17,845
but you need to give us
a little more to go on here.

247
00:21:19,525 --> 00:21:25,088
Garland Briggs is the best pilot
l've ever known.

248
00:21:25,264 --> 00:21:29,394
He was born with hardware
most of us only dream about.

249
00:21:29,969 --> 00:21:31,732
l can tell you this:

250
00:21:32,137 --> 00:21:38,804
His disappearance has implications
that go so far beyond national security

251
00:21:38,978 --> 00:21:42,345
the Cold War seems like a case
of the sniffles.

252
00:21:50,789 --> 00:21:55,624
The engine's fine,
the axle should be okay.

253
00:21:57,229 --> 00:21:59,754
How did you get so good at this?

254
00:22:00,599 --> 00:22:02,066
